  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">JaneliaSciComp/workstation 9.20.1 is a specialized scientific software tool developed primarily at Janelia Research Campus, with 156 downloads and 500 views recorded on Zenodo since its 2025 release. It has been cited in two peer-reviewed articles published in eLife, both focused on Drosophila neuroscience, signaling early but meaningful uptake within a focused research community.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Version 9.20.1 of the JaneliaSciComp workstation represents a versioned software release from a collaborative team of more than eighteen contributors affiliated primarily with Janelia Research Campus and the Howard Hughes Medical Institute. Archived openly on Zenodo and linked to its GitHub source tree, the release follows established open-science stewardship practices, including persistent DOI assignment and a clear versioning relationship to the broader software lineage. Its green open-access status ensures that researchers worldwide can access and download the tool without restriction.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Measured adoption is modest but concrete. With 156 downloads and 500 views on Zenodo, the tool is seeing active engagement from users who have moved beyond browsing to acquisition. For a highly specialized instrument-adjacent software package in the life sciences, these figures reflect a purposeful user base rather than broad general interest, which is consistent with tools designed to support large-scale neuroimaging and data management workflows.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The two citations to date both originate from a large-scale Drosophila split-GAL4 driver line resource published in eLife, involving international consortia spanning institutions in the United States, Germany, and Australia \u2014 including the Howard Hughes Medical Institute, the Allen Institute for Brain Science, Columbia University, and the University of Queensland, among others. These citing works are themselves well-cited, with a median citation count of approximately 17, suggesting that the workstation software is embedded in research that carries real downstream influence within the Drosophila neuroscience community.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Overall, JaneliaSciComp/workstation 9.20.1 exhibits the early-stage impact profile typical of domain-specific research infrastructure software: limited in breadth but precise in its scientific niche. Its role as an enabling tool for complex neurogenetic data workflows positions it as a quiet but functional contributor to an active and internationally distributed research program. Continued versioning and open archiving will be important for tracking and sustaining its scholarly footprint over time.</p>",
